<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Additional tier 1 capital securities are bonds=
 issued by banks that lose value if the bank fails or comes close to failin=
g. Credit Suisse Group AG failed this year, and its <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31860043.264406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZ=
XJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjAvdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3Nl=
LWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNjIxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA2MjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB93568479" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  $17 billion =
of AT1 securities</a> were written down to zero.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The holders of these bonds were very angry, both because they los=
t money=C2=A0and because they thought that they were treated unfairly. In s=
ome sense this was fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0the whole point of AT1s is to make t=
he AT1 holders angry when a bank fails, instead of making taxpayers angry =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but there was a potential negative consequence, which is tha=
t if investors got too aggrieved about how Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s AT1s wer=
e treated, they wouldn=E2=80=99t buy=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>banks=E2=80=
=99 AT1 securities, which would mean that other banks would have less loss-=
absorbing capital for future crises. Banking regulators worried about this=
=C2=A0and took pains to reassure investors that the Credit Suisse experienc=
e would not be repeated. I was a bit less worried. <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31860043.264406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTcvYmFua3Mtd2FudC1hLWJyZWFrLWZyb=
20tdGhlLWZkaWM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1=
dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN=
0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc25c1e35" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally my own view of the co=
rrect regulatory response here is something like =E2=80=9Cmemories in finan=
cial markets are extremely short, and any time a bond investor indignantly =
huffs that she will never buy some type of bond again, she=E2=80=99ll be bu=
ying it within a week.=E2=80=9D You have a meeting with AT1 investors, they=
 say =E2=80=9Cyou need to make sure that these bonds can never lose money,=
=E2=80=9D you nod and say =E2=80=9Cof course, of course,=E2=80=9D you wait =
six minutes, you forget all about it. I am not sure that will work here but=
 I don=E2=80=99t think I=E2=80=99d bet against it.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, well. The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/31860043.264406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRp=
Y2xlcy90aHJlZS1tb250aHMtYWZ0ZXItbG9zaW5nLTE3LWJpbGxpb24tb24tY3JlZGl0LXN1aXN=
zZS10aGUtYm9uZC1tYXJrZXQtaXMtY2FyZWZyZWUtMWVjYzAyNzc_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eW=
Fob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4104861b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal rep=
orts</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week, Spain-headquartered bank BBVA said =
it had issued =E2=82=AC1 billion ($1.1 billion) in so-called Additional Tie=
r 1, or AT1, securities. This market was upended in March when, in the proc=
ess of rescuing Credit Suisse, Swiss regulators wiped out the entire $17 bi=
llion value of its AT1s. Three months later, BBVA got bids for three times =
the issue on offer. Bank of Cyprus also sold new AT1s last week.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both wanted to test whether the door of the AT=
1 market was open, and the answer has been a resounding yes.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It speaks to how short-lived soul-searching in=
 the bond market has been. Back in March, the Bloomberg Global Contingent C=
apital index lost 15% of its value in just a few days. A big concern was th=
at Swiss regulators didn=E2=80=99t wipe out Credit Suisse shares, which app=
eared to violate the seniority of debt over equity.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Returns since the start of March are still neg=
ative and yields are above 8%. But in terms of the spread above interest ra=
tes, AT1 debt is back to 2022 levels, and around where it was in the 2014 t=
o 2016 period. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In short: Once the impact of central banks rai=
sing interest rates is taken into account, banks may actually be getting ch=
eaper AT1 funding.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CBond markets have short memories=E2=
=80=9D is one of the more reliable theses in financial markets. Elsewhere i=
n <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31860043.264406/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMjEvY3JlZGl=
0LXN1aXNzZS1zLWRlbWlzZS1ibGFtZWQtaW4tYm9uZGhvbGRlci1zdWl0LW9uLW55LWJhbmtlcn=
M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYyMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjIxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB93601ef4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s angry AT1 hol=
ders</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A group of Credit Suisse Group AG=E2=80=99s Eu=
ropean bondholders who were part of the $17 billion wipe-out in the bank=E2=
=80=99s demise sued its former executives, pointing to a =E2=80=9Cbroken cu=
lture=E2=80=9D and a series of scandals they trace to its New York-based in=
vestment banking operation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bondholders based in Paris, Luxembourg, and St=
. Peter Port, Guernsey argue that self-serving executives chased short-term=
 returns and bonuses from overly risky deals, resorting to unethical and il=
legal practices to acquire and keep high-revenue customers. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhile Credit Suisse began as a conser=
vative Swiss private bank, the vast majority of the people who were respons=
ible for its demise were not staid Swiss bankers, but, rather, sharp-elbowe=
d New York investment bankers,=E2=80=9D according to the complaint.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, but absorbing the losses caused by sharp-=
elbowed New York investment bankers is why AT1s exist.</p>
