<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This, from last week, is <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31860043.264406/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmN=
vbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zZXNhbWUtYWxsZXJneS1zdWZmZXJlcnMtd2FudGVkLXdhcm5pbmctbGFiZW=
xzLXRoZXktZ290LW1vcmUtc2VzYW1lLTI4M2M3MGNlP21vZD1ocF9saXN0Yl9wb3Mx/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cB3c2f83e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">one of the best stories you=E2=80=99ll e=
ver read</a> about how regulation works:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Congress passed legislation intended to make l=
ife better for people allergic to sesame seeds. Instead, it made things wor=
se.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bill, passed with overwhelming bipartisan =
support and signed into law by President Biden in 2021, requires manufactur=
ers to label sesame on their products starting this year.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response, some companies began adding sesam=
e to products that hadn=E2=80=99t included it in the past=E2=80=94saying it=
 was safer to add sesame and label it, rather than certify they had elimina=
ted all traces of it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People with sesame allergies say the result is=
 fewer sesame-free food options, as well as new and unexpected risks from s=
esame in foods they used to eat without worry.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The issue is that it is hard to eliminate trac=
e amounts of sesame, and the law now requires food manufacturers to label s=
esame as an allergen. Not putting sesame on the label effectively constitut=
es a promise that there is no sesame in the product, and if there is a litt=
le bit then you get in trouble:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Advising that the product =E2=80=
=9Cmay contain=E2=80=9D sesame on the label isn=E2=80=99t a practical solut=
ion since a trace amount of sesame detected could trigger a recall, the bak=
ers group said. The Food and Drug Administration considers =E2=80=9Cmay con=
tain=E2=80=9D a voluntary advisory that isn=E2=80=99t a substitute for good=
 manufacturing practices meant to ensure that a product is allergen-free, a=
nd finding an undeclared allergen could be grounds for ordering a recall.=
=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you say that the product=C2=A0<em>defin=
itely=C2=A0</em>contains sesame, then you are immunized from trouble. So yo=
u just chuck some sesame into everything, change the labels, and you=E2=80=
=99re fine. It is easier to make sure that there is sesame than that there =
isn=E2=80=99t, so that=E2=80=99s what companies do.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Everything is like this? There are huge areas =
of regulation where the most straightforward approach is to look at the gia=
nt book of rules and say =E2=80=9Cno thank you, I want=C2=A0out of this ent=
irely.=E2=80=9D Making non-sesame food products is a heavily regulated busi=
ness with huge risks if you mess up; making sesame-based food products just=
 lets you escape from that regulatory regime, so you might as well throw in=
 some sesame.</p>
