<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] =E2=80=9CWe find that firms=E2=80=99 perce=
ived cost of capital comoves with standard estimates of the financial cost =
of capital (based on the earnings yield or the Capital Asset Pricing Model,=
 CAPM, as well as interest rates) and we cannot reject that the estimate is=
 close to 1 on average. We do, however, find substantial firm-level heterog=
eneity in the dynamic incorporation of the financial cost of capital. This =
heterogeneity may reflect that firms use richer models than the CAPM to cal=
culate their perceived cost of capital or it may reflect mistakes in percep=
tions of the financial cost of capital.=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] Very loosely: A company=E2=80=99s WACC is =
not really the expected return to its investors, because its cost of debt i=
s tax-affected, but the cost of capital of an entirely equity-funded compan=
y more or less is the expected return on its shares.</p>
</div>
